          "body": "The negotiation of 29:15-20 introduces Laban at his most plausible. His offer of wages appears generous (29:15); his response to Jacob's proposal sounds affirming (29:19). But Laban never confirms which daughter Jacob is contracting for in writing or before witnesses — an omission he will exploit. The narrator's comment on Jacob's seven years is one of Scripture's most celebrated lines: 'they seemed to him but a few days because of his love for her' (29:20). The compression of years into days is not naivety — it is the witness of love's power to redeem time. Song of Solomon 8:7 insists that 'many waters cannot quench love'; Jacob's seven years demonstrate the claim. Yet the same verse that celebrates Jacob's love prepares the reader for the bitterest irony. A man who has waited seven years in love is precisely the man who cannot easily recover from what the morning of 29:25 reveals. Love made the seven years easy; it also made the betrayal catastrophic."
