          "body": "The four birth-narratives of 29:32-35 follow an identical rhythm: conceive, bear, name, explain the name. But the explanation of each name marks a spiritual movement. Reuben: 'the LORD has seen my affliction' — she is still hoping Jacob will love her (29:32). Simeon: 'the LORD has heard that I am unloved' — she is still processing her pain, but she is hearing God hear her (29:33). Levi: 'now my husband will become attached to me' — she is still looking horizontally, still expecting Jacob to turn (29:34). Judah: 'this time I will praise the LORD' — she stops speaking about Jacob entirely (29:35). The fourth name is not explained in terms of her marriage at all. She has found a different object for her attention. Jonathan Edwards (Religious Affections) argues that true religious affection always terminates on God and not on the goods God gives; Leah's fourth birth-narrative enacts exactly that movement. She receives the gift (a son) and gives the praise to the Giver without mentioning the gift's secondary benefit to her standing with Jacob. Judah's name encodes that praise permanently — and Judah's descendants will include David (Ruth 4:18-22), and through David, the Son of David who is the Lion of the tribe of Judah (Revelation 5:5). The unloved wife's act of praise becomes the name of the messianic tribe."
