          "body": "Genesis 29 is not a domestic episode inserted to humanize the patriarchal narrative. It is the structural foundation of the twelve-tribe nation. Of Jacob's twelve sons, six come from Leah (Reuben, Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar, Zebulun), two from Bilhah/Rachel (Dan, Naphtali), two from Zilpah/Leah (Gad, Asher), and two from Rachel (Joseph, Benjamin). The chapter begins the sequence by which all twelve will eventually be born. Leah's four sons in chapter 29 alone represent the priestly tribe (Levi), the royal-messianic tribe (Judah), and two others. Every subsequent reference to 'the twelve tribes of Israel' in Exodus, Numbers, Deuteronomy, the prophets, and Revelation traces back to this household of unresolved love and sovereign compensation. James 1:1 addresses 'the twelve tribes who are dispersed abroad'; Revelation 7:4-8 seals 144,000 from the twelve tribes. The genealogical stakes of Genesis 29 are therefore eschatological. Gordon Wenham (WBC) notes that 'the founding of the nation was achieved not through ideal conditions but through rivalry, suffering, and deception — all superintended by the LORD who saw what human eyes ignored.' The chapter does not resolve its pain; it plants its promise in the middle of that pain, and the promise outlasts the pain by millennia."
