        "range": "29:1-14",
        "excerpt": "When Jacob saw Rachel the daughter of Laban his mother's brother, and the sheep of Laban his mother's brother, Jacob went up and rolled the stone from the mouth of the well and watered the flock.",
        "body": "The chapter opens with a narrative economy that has long been recognized as a formal literary type-scene. Jacob arrives at a well, shepherds are gathered, a young woman approaches with her flock, a stranger waters the animals, an introduction follows, and the woman runs home to tell her father. Gordon Wenham (WBC, Genesis 16-50) and Robert Alter (The Art of Biblical Narrative) both identify this pattern as a biblical convention for announcing a divinely arranged betrothal. The convention's power lies in what it withholds: no angel, no explicit divine direction, no voice from heaven. God's guidance is embedded in the narrative structure itself — the reader, not the characters, sees the providential hand.\n\nThe well in vv. 2-3 functions as more than a setting. In the ancient Near East, wells were communal infrastructure and social gathering points, controlled by local custom (the assembled-flocks rule of v. 3 reflects genuine pastoral practice). Jacob's act of rolling the stone alone (v. 10), while the local shepherds are waiting for all the flocks to gather, is a calculated deviation from custom — an act of strength and urgency that cannot be explained by normal behavior. The text's triple repetition of 'Laban his mother's brother' in v. 10 (appearing three times in the Hebrew of that single verse) is not accidental — it marks every dimension of the encounter (Rachel, Laban, the sheep) as connected to the mission Jacob was sent on. He has arrived.\n\nLaban's welcome (vv. 13-14) reads warmly but plants the chapter's central tension. 'Surely you are my bone and my flesh' (v. 14) echoes the language of the marriage covenant in Genesis 2:23 and of tribal solidarity in 2 Samuel 5:1 — it is the strongest possible language of belonging. But Laban's subsequent behavior shows that kinship language can be weaponized. The embrace and the kiss of v. 13 are genuine and manipulative simultaneously — Laban recognizes a valuable kinsman and begins to calculate.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Galal* (to roll, vv. 3, 8, 10) — the stone rolled by the assembled shepherds is rolled by Jacob alone, signaling extraordinary strength or extraordinary urgency, likely both. *Akh* (surely, v. 14) is an emphatic particle marking a definitive conclusion — Laban's kinship claim is asserted, not merely suggested. The three-fold *ach* (brother/relative) of v. 10 in the BSB reflects the Hebrew's insistent repetition — the narrator is marking every part of Jacob's act as kin-motivated."
