        "body": "The labor negotiation of vv. 15-20 is Laban at his most skillfully ambiguous. His opening question — 'Should you therefore serve me for nothing? Tell me, what shall your wages be?' (v. 15) — is formally generous but practically a trap. By inviting Jacob to name his price, Laban gains information about what Jacob most desires. Jacob's desire is transparent: Rachel (v. 18). By offering the labor-for-daughter arrangement, Jacob has exposed himself and given Laban complete leverage.\n\nThe narrator's insertion of the daughters' description in vv. 16-17 is carefully placed. It comes between Laban's offer and Jacob's counter-proposal, suggesting that what Jacob is about to request is driven by what he has just seen: 'Rachel was beautiful of form and face' (v. 17). Leah's 'weak eyes' (*ayin rakh*, v. 17) has generated considerable scholarly discussion — it may mean soft/delicate (a possible beauty), dull (a deficiency), or simply unremarkable. The contrast with Rachel is the narrator's point, not a precise medical description. Derek Kidner (Tyndale OT Commentary on Genesis) suggests the description is 'deliberately left ambiguous' to avoid making Leah entirely unattractive, since the narrative needs the reader to understand Laban's substitution as at least plausible.\n\nLaban's acceptance of Jacob's proposal (v. 19: 'It is better that I give her to you than to give her to another man') is technically agreement but practically evasive. He never says Rachel's name. He says 'her.' The agreement that Jacob hears as a contract for Rachel is an agreement Laban will interpret as referring to a daughter of his choosing. The ambiguity is not incidental — it is the legal gap through which Laban will drive the substitution of v. 23.\n\nVerse 20 is one of the Old Testament's great lyric moments. Seven years compressed into 'but a few days because of his love for her' — *ahavah*, the same word used for Isaac's love for Rebekah (24:67) and for the love that the Song of Solomon celebrates (Song 2:4; 8:6-7). Love is the chapter's most powerful human force, and it is on display here at full strength. The irony is that this same love — which makes seven years feel like days — will make the morning of v. 25 feel catastrophic. The narrator is building the reader's investment in Jacob's love precisely so the betrayal lands with full force.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ahav* (loved, v. 18) and *ahavah* (love, v. 20) share the same root — the noun form emphasizes that Jacob's attachment is not passing attraction but settled, costly commitment. *Yapheh to'ar viyaphat mar'eh* (beautiful of form and face, v. 17) is a superlative double-description also used of Joseph in Genesis 39:6 — the same family trait, the same kind of dangerous beauty."
